The updated Firestore security rules should be:

```javascript
rules_version = '2';

service cloud.firestore {
 match /databases/{database}/documents {
 // Allow users to read and write their own prescriptions
 match /users/{userId}/prescriptions/{prescriptionId} {
 allow read, write: if request.auth != null && request.auth.uid == userId;
 }

 // Deny all other access
 match /{document=**} {
 allow read, write: if false;
 }
 }
}
```

This structure provides several benefits:

1. **User-specific data**: Each user's prescriptions are stored under `users/{userId}/prescriptions/`
2. **Security**: Users can only access their own prescriptions
3. **Scalability**: Multiple prescriptions per user are automatically organized
4. **Easy querying**: You can easily fetch all prescriptions for a specific user

The data structure will look like this in Firestore:
```
users/
 ├── {userId1}/
 │ └── prescriptions/
 │ ├── {prescriptionId1}
 │ ├── {prescriptionId2}
 │ └── ...
 └── {userId2}/
 └── prescriptions/
 ├── {prescriptionId1}
 └── ...
```

Each prescription document will contain:
- `summary`: The complete PrescriptionSummary object
- `savedAt`: Timestamp when saved
- `title`: Auto-generated title with date
- `userId`: The user's Firebase Auth UID

Update your Firestore rules in the Firebase Console with the rules I provided above, and the save functionality will work properly for authenticated users with proper data isolation."}]},{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"
